Difference between static and non-static methods in Java
--------------------------------------------------------

Case 1: public long maximumSubarraySum(int[] arr, int k)
- This works because you usually call it through an OBJECT.
  Example:
    Solution obj = new Solution();
    obj.maximumSubarraySum(arr, k);
- Non-static methods belong to objects, so you must create an object first.

Case 2: public long sum(int[] arr, int k)
- This did NOT work in your SLIDINGWINDOWBASICS class because you tried:
    System.out.println(sum(arr, k));
- But 'main' is static, and you called 'sum' directly without an object.
- Compiler error: "non-static method sum(int[], int) cannot be referenced from a static context".

Rule of Thumb:
- static methods → belong to the CLASS, can be called directly inside static methods like main.
- non-static methods → belong to OBJECTS, must be called using an object reference.

Fix Options:
1. Make the method static:
    public static long sum(int[] arr, int k) { ... }
    System.out.println(sum(arr, k));

2. Keep it non-static but call via object:
    SLIDINGWINDOWBASICS obj = new SLIDINGWINDOWBASICS();
    System.out.println(obj.sum(arr, k));
